title: For Sale/Trade:  McGowen .280 Remington Ackley Improved Barrel for Savage
postcontent:
Here are the specs:

.280 Ackley Improved chamber - widely considered Ackley's finest wildcat, this cartridge sits nicely between the under-performing .280 Remington and the hyper-active 7mm Magnum. The cartridge has seen a big resurgence in long-range shooting since being SAAMI spec'd. It is an ideal long-range cartridge (think 1,200-1,500 yards).
28" length - will push a 7mm bullet at speeds very close to 7mm Mag with substantially less recoil and requiring about 20 grains less powder charge.
Small (or standard) shank - fits most Savage receivers with the exception of the short magnums - if you have a .25-06, .270, .280, or .30-06 this is a drop-in part. Magnum rifles will require a new bolt-face.
1:8" twist - fast twist allows for shooting the heaviest and longest bullets of the 7mm family with great stability.
11 degree target crown - the gold standard of target/long-range shooting.
Bull barrel profile - a heavy barrel profile that is not as susceptible to POI change due to barrel heat and is also more rigid than traditional tapers for extremely consistent accuracy. The additional barrel weight dramatically reduces recoil for quicker follow up shots.

McGowen is widely considered a very fine barrel maker offering product at an affordable price. This barrel is stainless steel, hand-lapped, and completely custom. Although the barrel has not been fired, I would expect no less than 1 MOA accuracy, and probably much better if you do your part. I've shot lesser barrels down to sub-1/3 MOA. If you've never shot out of a custom barrel, you will find the results vs. a factory Savage barrel quite startling in terms of improved accuracy.

If you are local I am willing to help you head-space your new barrel. Please note that there is a slight nick and a few small scratches on the barrel that were incurred during shipment. The blemishes will not affect accuracy, and assuming you will be Cera-Koting the rifle are a non-issue. See photos.

title: For Sale/Trade:  .38 special premium home defense rounds
postcontent:
$50 for both or trade for ammo: 9mm, .40 S&W or .45acp.  One box of the premium Magsafe Defender and one box Magtech First Defense.  

Magtech First Defense:

These rounds are designed with a 100% solid copper bullet, unlike traditional hollow points that contain a lead core covered by a copper jacket. Copper jackets could tear away when fired, causing a loss of weight and a corresponding loss of power. However, Magtech First Defense solid copper bullets have no jacket to split or tear away, ensuring every round you fire meets its target with maximum impact and effectiveness. Trust the bullet that delivers deep penetration and devastating expansion... the kind that stops a threat in its tracks.

MagSafe Defender:

DESIGNED FOR PERFECT PENETRATION DEPTH
MagSafe's revolutionary design uses large lead shotgun pellets rather than solid lead for a bullet's core. The earliest versions (1986-1987) used small pellets, like the #6 shot a competitor uses for their "Silver" line of frangible ammo.

Early in the design process, hundreds of videotaped test shots were made into ordnance gelatin. Then, viewed in slow motion, you could see how a core's pellet size and pattern created the greatest wound damage for any given caliber.

It was quickly learned that using much larger #2 or #3 shot gave perfect penetration depth in gelatin or flesh-form 10 to 13 inches (two to three times as much penetration as our competitors). A large man's chest is only 12 inches thick from front to back, and any more penetration than that was wasted energy which would endanger innocent people.

That was the first goal reached - ammunition which won't overpenetrate a torso and hurt or kill innocent bystanders.

REDUCED RICOCHET HAZARD
One side benefit of using huge shot pellets is the reduction of ricochets, because larger objects are affected more by rotational forces. Tests showed that MagSafe Ammo won't even glance off slimy, wet boards at the most shallow of angles. They also don't ricochet off windshields, car doors or interior house walls. And, most importantly, they won't glance off bone.

ANOTHER GOAL WAS REACHED. "CONTROLLED-CORE TECHNOLOGY"
For almost a year, experimentation with shot placement within the bullet's jacket continued, looking for a fan-shaped pellet wound channel. It was felt that the wider the pattern the better the chance of hitting vital organs, even with a poolry-placed shot.

By arranging pellets in specific patterns, literally stacking them in place one at a time, by hand, bullets could be designed to work nearly any way wanted - maybe deeper penetration, or wider wound channel, some even to break apart in sheetrock walls.

To stabilize the pellet patterns until the instant of impact, dozens of types of epoxy resins were tested. A custom blend with perfect properties was found - it is easily broken apart at impact, yet tough enough to launch at twice the velocity of normal bullets.

No other ammo uses high-tech resins or pellets put onto specific patterns by hand.

This Smith and Wesson Model 19-2 is chambered in .357 magnum with a 4 pinned barrel and 6 round capacity. This firearm has the original old-style rear sight leaf screw placement. This gun contains all original parts/grips 

The Model 19 was Smith and Wesson's first .357 magnum mass produced handgun, and the '-4 variant was the second variant ever produced. The Model 19 was produced in blued carbon steel or nickel-plated steel with wood or rubber combat grips, an adjustable rear sight, semi-target hammer, serrated combat-type trigger, and was available in 2.5", 4", or 6-inch barrel lengths. The Model 19 was produced from 1957 to November 1999.
